The interaction of Van-AuNPs with Gram-positive bacteria was examined. When Van-AuNPs were mixed with Gram-positive S. aureus cells and centrifuged, the color of the supernatant faded and the precipitate turned red (Fig. 4
                        A). Moreover, the UV–vis absorption of supernatant at 519 nm decreased with the increase of the concentrations of S. aureus cells (Fig. 4B); there is a good linear correlation between the absorption of the supernatant and the concentration of S. aureus cells in the concentration range of 0−8 × 108 cells/mL (Fig. 4C). The limit of UV–vis spectroscopic detection of S. aureus was approximately 1 × 107 cells/mL (signal/noise ratio >3:1). However, when Van-AuNPs were mixed with Gram-negative E. coli cells and were centrifuged, the UV–vis absorption of supernatant at 519 nm only slightly decreased with the increase of the concentration of E. coli cells (Fig. 5
                        ). These results indicate that the as-prepared Van-AuNPs had a strong interaction with Gram-positive S. aureus and a weak interaction with Gram-negative E. coli. We further investigated the interactions of other species of Gram-positive bacteria B. subtilis and M. luteus with Van-AuNPs (Fig. 6
                        ). The absorbance of supernatants of B. subtilis and M. luteus cells decreased even more significantly than that of S. aureus, suggesting that B. subtilis and M. luteus cells could also bind strongly with Van-AuNPs.

To estimate the practicability of the colorimetric assay, we detected the real samples containing S. aureus. Orange juice and tap water containing different concentrations of S. aureus cells were tested. After incubated with Van-AuNPs and washed with water, the photographs of these bacterial cells on the nitrocellulose membrane strips were taken (Fig. 9
                        ). The colors of these spots were transformed into gray values, and compared with the gray values of the spots of S. aureus with known numbers of cells. The detection recoveries are in the range of 95–103% with relative standard deviations of 1–10% (Table 1
                        ), showing that this method has great potential for the quantitative detection of Gram-positive bacteria in real samples. Compared with existing identification methods for S. aureus (Table S1), if 1 CFU is approximately equal to 1 bacterial cell (experiential), this colorimetric assay shows a comparable detection limit.
